            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#VM #JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>ἐνθάδε κεῖτε
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name>Δάφρος</name></persName> <g ref="#staurogram">𐆠</g>
                    <lb n="3"/><expan><abbr>σ<am><g ref="#staurogram">𐆠</g></am>ω</abbr><ex>τήρ</ex></expan>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text after Orsi and photograph</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>Carini, Kaibel: ΔΑΦΡΟΕ</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Here lies Daphros</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The form Daphros is not otherwise attested, and Kaibel speculates that Daphnos was intended (although Kaibel, following Carini, actually read Daphroe, which is also unparalleled). The combination of sigma, staurogram, omega between the two doves in the third line presumably signifies 'soter', 'saviour'. Kaibel simply reproduces Carini's text, without included reference to the symbols on the stone, which Carini did report (overleaf on p.34). Orsi transcribed the text and its symbols accurately in his taccuini in 1888.</p>
            </div>
